---
import BaseLayout from '../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';

const siteUrl = Astro.site?.href ?? 'https://paddletoday.com/';
const websiteId = new URL('/#website', siteUrl).href;
const organizationId = new URL('/#organization', siteUrl).href;
const aboutUrl = new URL('/about/', siteUrl).href;
const aboutStructuredData = {
  '@context': 'https://schema.org',
  '@type': 'AboutPage',
  '@id': `${aboutUrl}#about-page`,
  name: 'About Paddle Today',
  description:
    'Learn how Paddle Today ranks paddling routes, checks river and weather data, and explains when a recommendation needs extra caution.',
  url: aboutUrl,
  isPartOf: {
    '@id': websiteId,
  },
  about: {
    '@id': organizationId,
  },
};
---

<BaseLayout
  title="About Paddle Today | How Route Scores Work"
  description="Learn how Paddle Today ranks paddling routes, checks river and weather data, and explains when a recommendation needs extra caution."
  structuredData={aboutStructuredData}
>
  <section class="info-hero">
    <p class="eyebrow">About Paddle Today</p>
    <h1>How Paddle Today makes a recommendation</h1>
    <p class="muted">
      Paddle Today is a planning tool for choosing where to paddle today. It combines river level, recent trend, weather, route notes, and data freshness into one ranked board so you can start with the strongest options instead of checking every source manually.
    </p>
    <p class="muted">
      The score is not a safety guarantee. It is a shortcut for deciding what deserves a closer look before you drive.
    </p>
    <div class="info-hero__actions">
      <a class="river-link river-link--inline" href="/">See today's board</a>
      <a class="river-link river-link--inline river-link--ghost" href="/request-river/">Request a river</a>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="info-grid" aria-label="How to read Paddle Today scores">
    <article class="info-card">
      <p class="eyebrow">Score</p>
      <h2>What the rating means</h2>
      <ul class="compact-list">
        <li><strong>Strong:</strong> river level, trend, weather, and data support all line up well.</li>
        <li><strong>Good:</strong> a solid option, but one factor may deserve a re-check.</li>
        <li><strong>Fair:</strong> possible for the right paddler, but there is a clear caution.</li>
        <li><strong>No-go:</strong> not recommended for most paddlers today.</li>
      </ul>
    </article>

    <article class="info-card">
      <p class="eyebrow">Inputs</p>
      <h2>Where the data comes from</h2>
      <p class="muted">
        The board uses USGS gauge readings where available, weather forecasts, route distance and access notes, and published or curated river-level guidance. Each route page links back to the important source material so you can verify before you launch.
      </p>
    </article>

    <article class="info-card">
      <p class="eyebrow">Support</p>
      <h2>What data support means</h2>
      <p class="muted">
        A well-supported route has a fresh, relevant gauge and clearer threshold guidance. Some uncertainty means the gauge may be indirect, the guidance may be thinner, or the latest read needs a closer source check.
      </p>
    </article>
  </section>

  <section class="info-grid" aria-label="What to verify before paddling">
    <article class="info-card">
      <p class="eyebrow">Weather</p>
      <h2>Why weather can lower a score</h2>
      <p class="muted">
        Cold air, wind, storms, and incoming rain can make a technically usable river a poor choice for many paddlers. When that happens, the route can still be possible, but the site intentionally ranks it lower.
      </p>
    </article>

    <article class="info-card">
      <p class="eyebrow">Limits</p>
      <h2>What can still change</h2>
      <p class="muted">
        Fast rain, debris, ice, access closures, parking rules, and local hazards can change faster than the board refreshes. Treat the recommendation as a first pass, then verify the source links and conditions on the ground.
      </p>
    </article>

    <article class="info-card">
      <p class="eyebrow">Coverage</p>
      <h2>Why some routes are missing</h2>
      <p class="muted">
        Paddle Today only works well when a route has enough source data to make a useful read. If you can share a put-in, take-out, and relevant USGS gauge, that route is much easier to add.
      </p>
    </article>
  </section>

  <section class="info-panel">
    <p class="eyebrow">Common sources</p>
    <h2>The site leans on public data and route-specific references.</h2>
    <p class="muted">
      Not every route uses every source. The route page is still the source of truth for that specific recommendation, but these are the sources Paddle Today uses most often:
    </p>
    <ul class="compact-list">
      <li><strong>USGS Water Data:</strong> live gauge readings, recent trend, and gauge freshness.</li>
      <li><strong>National Weather Service:</strong> hourly forecast, wind, temperature, storm risk, and nearby station observations.</li>
      <li><strong>NOAA MRMS QPE:</strong> recent radar-estimated rainfall around the route.</li>
      <li><strong>State DNR pages:</strong> Minnesota, Wisconsin, and Iowa route maps, river-level notes, public-water-access records, and water-trail guidance.</li>
      <li><strong>Local city and county pages:</strong> put-in/take-out access, park hours, parking rules, launch details, and closure context.</li>
      <li><strong>Trip reports and paddling references:</strong> sources such as MilesPaddled when official river-level thresholds are incomplete.</li>
      <li><strong>Map sources:</strong> OpenStreetMap, OpenFreeMap, and MapLibre for map display and access context.</li>
    </ul>
  </section>

  <section class="info-panel">
    <p class="eyebrow">How to use it</p>
    <h2>Start with the board, then verify the route.</h2>
    <ul class="compact-list">
      <li>Use the top picks to find the best-looking routes first.</li>
      <li>Set a city or ZIP code if drive time matters.</li>
      <li>Open the route page and check the gauge, weather, access notes, and source links.</li>
      <li>Re-check conditions before driving, especially after rain or during cold-weather shoulder season.</li>
    </ul>
  </section>
</BaseLayout>
